The chief change introduced by the reform was the combination of the local division of the people in 35 districts (to-ibus) with the Servian division. Neither the time of this reform (Mommsen rom. Gesch. 1. 796. ed. τ. dates it B.o. ²4¹) nor the number of the new centuries is exactly known ; it is most likely, however, that the 35 tribes were divided into 350 centuries. By the Servian constitution the people was divided into 5 classes according to property, and each class was sub- divided into itmwres and seniores. This division was applied to the tribes in such a way, that each tribe was divided according to property into 5 classes, each class according to age into two halvcs. Thus each of the 35 tribes contained 10 centur-ies, and 70 oentuxies (35 iuniorum and 35 seniorum) formed one class.
